SIMPLE: sanguine
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sanguine
<hw>San"guine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>sanguin</ets>, L. <ets>sanguineus</ets>, fr. <ets>sanguis</ets>
blood. Cf. <er>Sanguineous</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the
color of blood; red.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of his complexion he was <qex>sanguine</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like to that <qex>sanguine</qex> flower inscribed with woe.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized by abundance and active circulation of
blood; <as>as, a <ex>sanguine</ex> bodily temperament</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Warm; ardent; <as>as, a <ex>sanguine</ex>
temper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Anticipating the best; cheerfully optimistic; not
desponding; confident; full of hope; <as>as, <ex>sanguine</ex> of
success; a <ex>sanguine</ex> disposition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Warm; ardent; lively; confident; hopeful;
optimistic.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sanguine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sanguine
<hw>San"guine</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Blood color;
red.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything of a blood-red color, as cloth.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In <qex>sanguine</qex> and in pes he clad was all.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Bloodstone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Red crayon. See the Note under <er>Crayon</er>,
1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sanguine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sanguine
<hw>San"guine</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To stain with blood; to impart
the color of blood to; to ensanguine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sanguineless</ent>⟦br⟧
